Commands and agents:

  All seven slash commands (/spec, /plan, /build, /test, /code-simplify,
  /review, /ship) and the three specialist agents (code-reviewer,
  security-auditor, test-engineer) originate from agent-skills. Several
  command files have been edited to invoke a mixed set of skills drawn
  from both upstream sources, with all internal skill references
  rewritten to the mzyx-skills: namespace.

  One new command is original to this repository:
    /brainstorm  — wraps brainstorming as a verb in the pipeline

  Waza skills are imported without command stubs to avoid listing
  duplicates (a stub named the same as a skill would surface twice).
  Invoke them via the namespaced skill name (e.g. mzyx-skills:think)
  or rely on description-based auto-trigger.

Waza skill modifications:

  All eight waza skills retain their original logic. The only edits applied:
    - Removed the 🥷 emoji prefix instruction (every SKILL.md preamble)
    - Stripped Chinese-language trigger phrases from the `when_to_use:`
      frontmatter and Chinese examples from skill bodies
    - Functional regex patterns inside helper scripts (read/scripts/fetch.sh,
      health/scripts/collect-data.sh) that detect Chinese-platform login
      walls or AI-pattern phrases were left intact, since they are
      classifiers, not user-facing prose
    - No cross-reference renamespacing was needed: waza skills reference
      each other via bare slash names (/think, /hunt, etc.) which resolve
      to the corresponding command stubs in this plugin

Skill body edits:

  Several skill bodies originally contained internal cross-references
  prefixed with the upstream plugin names. All such prefixes have been
  rewritten to the mzyx-skills namespace so the skills resolve correctly
  under this plugin. Where references pointed to skills excluded from
  this set (the worktree skill), the reference was removed; where they
  pointed to skills that exist under a different name (the upstream
  systematic-debugging reference now targets debugging-and-error-recovery,
  and the upstream TDD reference now targets test-driven-development),
  the reference was retargeted to the retained skill.
